DURING TAKEOFF FROM RUNWAY 22, THE PILOT RPRTD THAT HE HAD A PROBLEM, THEN 
THERE WAS NO FURTHER COMM FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  SVRL WITNESSES SAW AN OBJECT 
FALL FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND ONE WITNESS OBSERVED THAT A 'HOOD' HAD OPENED.  THE 
AIRCRAFT WAS MNVRD ONTO FINAL APPROACH TO RUNWAY 36.  A WITNESS SAID THAT AS THE 
AIRCRAFT WAS LINING UP ON FINAL APCH, IT ENTERED A STEEP BANK AND DSCNDD OUT OF 
HIS SIGHT.  SUBSEQUENTLY, IT COLLIDED WITH TREES IN A 27 DEG DSCNT, 
CRASHED AND BURNED.  A BAG FROM THE NOSE BAGGAGE COMPARTMENT WAS FND 
NEAR THE DEP END OF RUNWAY 22.  NO PREIMPACT PART FAILURE OR SYSTEM 
MALFUNCTION OF THE AIRCRAFT WAS FND.  BEFORE THE FLIGHT, A RAMP PERSON 
OBSERVED THE PILOT SERVICING THE LEFT ENG WITH OIL, BUT HE DID NOT KNOW IF 
THE PILOT HAD SECURED THE BAGGAGE DOOR.  AN EXAM OF THE RCVRD DOOR 
ASSEMBLY FAILED TO DISCLOSE A MALFUNCTION OF THE REAR LAIR TRAFFIC CONTROLH ASSEMBLY. 
THE FORWARD LAIR TRAFFIC CONTROLH ASSEMBLY AREA WAS DESTROYED BY FIRE. 
THE PILOT DIVERTED HIS ATTENTION AND FAILED TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF THE 
AIRCRAFT, WHILE MANEUVERING FOR A PRECAUTIONARY LANDING.  FACTORS 
RELATED TO THE ACCIDENT WERE: THE UNSECURED BAGGAGE COMPARTMENT 
DOOR AND THE PILOT'S INADEQUATE PREFLIGHT. 
